<h2>History & Origins of Napa Valley</h2>

<p>Napa Valley's winemaking journey began in the 1840s when <strong>George Calvert Yount</strong> planted the region's first vineyard near present-day Yountville. However, it was <strong>Charles Krug</strong> who established the valley's first commercial winery in 1861, launching what would become California's most prestigious wine region.</p>

<p>The late 19th century marked Napa's golden age, with European immigrants like <strong>Jacob Schram</strong> (Schramsberg, 1862) and <strong>Gustav Niebaum</strong> (Inglenook, 1879) establishing wineries that still operate today. The Beringer brothers arrived from Germany in 1875, building their Rhine House and extensive cave system that demonstrated serious commitment to quality winemaking.</p>

<h3>Prohibition and Revival</h3>

<p>Prohibition (1920-1933) devastated Napa Valley, reducing active wineries from over 140 to fewer than 30. The region's renaissance began slowly in the 1940s with <strong>André Tchelistcheff</strong> joining Beaulieu Vineyard as winemaker. His introduction of French winemaking techniques and focus on Cabernet Sauvignon laid the foundation for Napa's future reputation.</p>

