<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Napa Valley AVA and Napa Valley sub-AVAs?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley AVA is the overarching appellation covering the entire valley, while sub-AVAs like Rutherford, Oakville, and Stags Leap District have more specific terroir characteristics. Sub-AVA wines typically command higher prices due to their distinct microclimates and soil compositions—for example, Rutherford's famous "dust" tannin profile or Carneros' cool-climate elegance. Wines labeled simply "Napa Valley" often blend grapes from multiple areas, offering excellent value while maintaining the region's quality standards.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Napa Valley wine good for beginners or too intense?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley offers excellent entry points for beginners, particularly Sauvignon Blanc from cooler areas like Carneros or value-driven Cabernet Sauvignon from valley floor producers. While cult Cabernets can be powerfully tannic and concentrated, many Napa wines are crafted in an approachable, fruit-forward style that's immediately enjoyable. Start with producers like Cakebread Cellars, Frank Family, or Frog's Leap, which make wines that showcase Napa's character without overwhelming new wine drinkers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why are Napa Valley wines so expensive compared to other California regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley's high prices reflect extremely limited vineyard land (only 45,000 acres total), premium terroir, and intense global demand that has driven vineyard prices to $200,000-$400,000 per acre. The region's reputation for world-class Cabernet Sauvignon, established by the 1976 Judgment of Paris, created a luxury market where scarcity meets prestige. Additionally, many Napa producers use expensive French oak, extended aging, and low-yield farming practices that increase production costs but enhance quality.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best way to serve Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Napa Cabernet at 60-65°F and decant for 1-2 hours to allow the wine's bold tannins to soften and complex aromatics to emerge. Use large Bordeaux-style glasses to concentrate the wine's powerful fruit and oak characteristics. Young Napa Cabernets (under 5 years) especially benefit from decanting, while well-aged bottles should be decanted carefully to separate any sediment that may have formed during cellaring.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I cellar Napa Valley wines before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignons are crafted to be approachable upon release but will develop additional complexity with 5-15 years of proper cellaring. Wines from prestigious sub-AVAs like Howell Mountain or Pritchard Hill can age gracefully for 20+ years due to their structured tannins and concentrated fruit. Napa Sauvignon Blanc and Pinot Noir are generally best consumed within 2-4 years of vintage, though exceptional examples from producers like Screaming Eagle or Araujo Estate can evolve beautifully for decades.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying Napa Valley wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Napa wines are similar—the valley's diverse microclimates produce dramatically different styles, from elegant Carneros Pinot Noir to powerful Howell Mountain Cabernet. Many buyers also overlook excellent value producers like Honig, Vincent Arroyo, or Peju in favor of cult names, missing wines that offer 80% of the quality at 40% of the price. Additionally, purchasing young, high-tannin Cabernets without proper cellaring plans often leads to disappointing early drinking experiences.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives to expensive Napa Valley Cabernet?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look to Sonoma County's Alexander Valley or Knights Valley for similar Cabernet styles at 30-50% less cost, or explore Paso Robles for bold, fruit-forward reds with excellent aging potential. Within Napa, seek out Cabernet Franc, Merlot, or Petit Verdot from top producers—these varieties offer the region's terroir expression at more accessible price points. Washington State's Columbia Valley and Argentina's Mendoza also produce structured, age-worthy Cabernets that rival Napa's quality while offering significant value.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Napa Valley sub-regions offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Calistoga and the northern valley floor provide excellent value, producing rich, approachable Cabernets without the premium pricing of Rutherford or Oakville. The Carneros region offers outstanding Pinot Noir and Chardonnay at prices significantly lower than Burgundian equivalents, while Atlas Peak and Mount Veeder produce distinctive mountain wines that are often undervalued compared to Howell Mountain. Look for wines simply labeled "Napa Valley" from reputable producers, as these often blend fruit from premium areas at accessible prices.</p>
